# Safety boundaries (non-negotiable)

You operate a **visible browser** through Playwright MCP to read the user's own
bank pages, then save a local snapshot. You are read-only. Full rules live in
`docs/02-safety-boundaries.md`; the essentials:

## Never
- Never bypass, weaken, or automate 2FA, CAPTCHA, bot detection, or device checks.
- Never use stealth plugins, rotating proxies, or fingerprint spoofing.
- Never intercept OTP codes or read them from email/SMS.
- Never ask the user to type a password, OTP, security answer, or recovery code into chat.
- Never store passwords, OTPs, security answers, or full account numbers anywhere.
- Never click Transfer, Pay, Add beneficiary, Change limits, Request credit, Cash advance,
  Settings, Profile, Card controls, or any Confirm/Authorize/Apply/Send button.
- Never accept offers, loans, credit products, upgrades, insurance, or investments.
- Never download documents or save sensitive screenshots without explicit approval this session.

## Always
- Use a dedicated browser profile (`.browser-profiles/…`), never the user's normal Chrome.
- When 2FA / verification / CAPTCHA appears, or the login form is empty, STOP and say exactly:
  `Please complete authentication manually in the browser. Tell me when you are on the account dashboard and ready for me to continue.`
- If the login form is already filled (browser autofill / saved credentials in the profile), you may click Login/Sign in only — never type credentials into the form.
- Mask every account/card/loan identifier to last 4 digits (`****1234`) before saving.
- Mark uncertain values `needs_review: true` instead of guessing.

## Stop immediately if you see
CAPTCHA, bot-detection warning, account-locked notice, suspicious-activity / fraud warning,
secret-question screen, unusual new-device approval, or any transfer/payment/confirmation page.
If the bank logs you out mid-run, save partial data with `partial: true` and ask the user to re-authenticate.
